SIMPLE: moving
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moving
<hw>Mov"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Changing place or
posture; causing motion or action; <as>as, a <ex>moving</ex> car, or
power</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Exciting movement of the mind or feelings; adapted
to move the sympathies, passions, or affections; touching; pathetic;
<as>as, a <ex>moving</ex> appeal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I sang an old <qex>moving</qex> story.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moving force</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a force
that accelerates, retards, or deflects the motion of a body.</cd> --
<col><b>Moving plant</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a leguminous plant
(<spn>Desmodium gyrans</spn>); -- so called because its leaflets have a
distinct automatic motion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moving</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Moving
<hw>Mov"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of changing place or
posture; esp., the act of changing one's dwelling place or place of
business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moving day</b></col>, <cd>a day when one moves; esp., a
day when a large number of tenants change their dwelling
place.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Movingly</ent>⟦br⟧
